üü¢ PART 1: JavaScript Basics
1Ô∏è‚É£ What is JavaScript?

Definition:
JavaScript is a programming language used to make web pages interactive and dynamic. It runs in browsers and servers.

Example:

console.log("Hello JavaScript");

2Ô∏è‚É£ Variables

Definition:
Variables store data values.

Example:

let name = "Gaurav";
const age = 23;
var city = "Pune";

var vs let vs const (Complete Explanation)
1Ô∏è‚É£ var (OLD ‚Äì avoid using)
üîπ Scope

Function-scoped

NOT block-scoped

if (true) {
  var city = "Pune";
}
console.log(city); // ‚úÖ Pune (accessible outside block)

üîπ Re-declaration (Allowed ‚ùå)
var x = 10;
var x = 20; // ‚úÖ No error (dangerous)

üîπ Re-assignment (Allowed)
var x = 10;
x = 30; // ‚úÖ allowed

üîπ Hoisting

Hoisted and initialized as undefined

console.log(a); // undefined
var a = 10;

‚ùå Problems with var

Can cause unexpected bugs

No block scope

Easily overwritten

2Ô∏è‚É£ let (MODERN & RECOMMENDED)
üîπ Scope

Block-scoped

if (true) {
  let name = "Gaurav";
}
console.log(name); // ‚ùå Error (not accessible)

üîπ Re-declaration (Not allowed ‚ùå)
let x = 10;
let x = 20; // ‚ùå Error

üîπ Re-assignment (Allowed)
let x = 10;
x = 20; // ‚úÖ allowed

üîπ Hoisting

Hoisted but NOT initialized

Lives in Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ)

console.log(a); // ‚ùå ReferenceError
let a = 10;

‚úÖ When to use let

When the value will change

Loop counters

Conditional variables

3Ô∏è‚É£ const (BEST & DEFAULT CHOICE ‚≠ê)
üîπ Scope

Block-scoped (same as let)

if (true) {
  const age = 23;
}
console.log(age); // ‚ùå Error

üîπ Re-declaration (Not allowed ‚ùå)
const x = 10;
const x = 20; // ‚ùå Error

üîπ Re-assignment (Not allowed ‚ùå)
const age = 23;
age = 24; // ‚ùå Error

üîπ IMPORTANT: Objects & Arrays with const

You can modify, but cannot reassign.

const user = { name: "Gaurav" };
user.name = "Ramane"; // ‚úÖ allowed

user = {}; // ‚ùå Error

üîπ Hoisting

Same as let (TDZ)

console.log(x); // ‚ùå Error
const x = 10;

‚úÖ When to use const

Default choice

Objects, arrays, functions

Values that should not be reassigned


3Ô∏è‚É£ Data Types

Definition:
Data types define the type of value stored.

Example:

let text = "Hello";      // string
let number = 10;        // number
let isActive = true;    // boolean
let data = null;        // null
let value;              // undefined

üü¢ PART 2: Operators


4Ô∏è‚É£ Operators

Definition:
Operators perform operations on values.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Arithmetic Operators

Definition:
Used to perform mathematical calculations.

Operators:
+ - * / % ** ++ --

Example:

let a = 10;
let b = 3;

console.log(a + b); // 13
console.log(a % b); // 1
console.log(a ** b); // 1000

2Ô∏è‚É£ Assignment Operators

Definition:
Used to assign values to variables.

Operators:
= += -= *= /= %= **=

Example:

let x = 10;
x += 5;  // x = 15
x *= 2;  // x = 30

3Ô∏è‚É£ Comparison Operators

Definition:
Used to compare two values and return true or false.

Operators:
== === != !== > < >= <=

Example:

console.log(5 == "5");   // true
console.log(5 === "5"); // false

4Ô∏è‚É£ Logical Operators

Definition:
Used to combine multiple conditions.

Operators:
&& || !

Example:

let age = 20;

console.log(age > 18 && age < 30); // true

5Ô∏è‚É£ Bitwise Operators (Advanced)

Definition:
Work at the binary (bit) level.

Operators:
& | ^ ~ << >> >>>

Example:

console.log(5 & 1); // 1

6Ô∏è‚É£ String Operators

Definition:
Used to concatenate strings.

Operators:
+ +=

Example:

let first = "Gaurav";
let last = "Ramane";

console.log(first + " " + last);

7Ô∏è‚É£ Ternary (Conditional) Operator

Definition:
Short form of if-else.

Syntax:
condition ? value1 : value2

Example:

let result = age >= 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor";

8Ô∏è‚É£ Type Operators

Definition:
Used to check data types or object relationships.

Operators:
typeof instanceof

Example:

console.log(typeof "Hello"); // string
console.log([] instanceof Array); // true


üü¢ PART 3: Conditions
5Ô∏è‚É£ if‚Äìelse

Definition:
Used to execute code based on conditions.

Example:

let age = 18;

if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("Adult");
} else {
  console.log("Minor");
}

6Ô∏è‚É£ switch

Definition:
Used when multiple conditions depend on one value.

Example:

let day = "Monday";

switch (day) {
  case "Monday":
    console.log("Start of week");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Other day");
}

üü¢ PART 4: Loops
7Ô∏è‚É£ for loop

Definition:
Used to repeat code multiple times.

Example:

for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}

8Ô∏è‚É£ while loop

Example:

let i = 1;
while (i <= 3) {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}

üü¢ PART 5: Functions
9Ô∏è‚É£ Function

Definition:
A function is a reusable block of code.

Example:

function greet(name) {
  return "Hello " + name;
}

console.log(greet("Gaurav"));

üîü Arrow Function

Definition:
Shorter syntax for functions.

Example:

const add = (a, b) => a + b;
console.log(add(5, 3));

üü¢ PART 6: Scope
1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Scope

Definition:
Scope defines where variables are accessible.

Example:

let x = 10;

function test() {
  let y = 5;
  console.log(x); // accessible
}

üü¢ PART 7: Closures ‚≠ê
1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Closure

Definition:
A function that remembers variables from its outer function.

Example:

function outer() {
  let count = 0;

  return function inner() {
    count++;
    console.log(count);
  };
}

const counter = outer();
counter();
counter();

üü¢ PART 8: Arrays
1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Array

Definition:
Stores multiple values in one variable.

Example:

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];
console.log(fruits[1]);

1Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ Array Methods

Example:

let numbers = [1, 2, 3];

numbers.push(4);
numbers.pop();

console.log(numbers);

üü¢ PART 9: Array Higher-Order Methods
1Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ map

Definition:
Transforms each element.

Example:

let nums = [1, 2, 3];
let doubled = nums.map(n => n * 2);

1Ô∏è‚É£6Ô∏è‚É£ filter

Example:

let nums = [1, 2, 3, 4];
let even = nums.filter(n => n % 2 === 0);

1Ô∏è‚É£7Ô∏è‚É£ reduce

Example:

let nums = [1, 2, 3];
let sum = nums.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);

üü¢ PART 10: Objects
1Ô∏è‚É£8Ô∏è‚É£ Object

Definition:
Stores data as key‚Äìvalue pairs.

Example:

let user = {
  name: "Gaurav",
  age: 23,
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
};

user.greet();

üü¢ PART 11: Destructuring
1Ô∏è‚É£9Ô∏è‚É£ Destructuring

Definition:
Extract values easily.

Example:

const user = { name: "Gaurav", age: 23 };
const { name, age } = user;

üü¢ PART 12: Spread & Rest
2Ô∏è‚É£0Ô∏è‚É£ Spread Operator

Example:

let a = [1, 2];
let b = [...a, 3, 4];

2Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Rest Operator

Example:

function sum(...numbers) {
  return numbers.reduce((a, b) => a + b);
}

üü¢ PART 13: Async JavaScript



Asynchronous JavaScript (DETAILED)
üîπ Why Async JavaScript Exists

JavaScript is single-threaded, meaning it can do one task at a time.

If JS waited for:

API calls

File reading

Database queries

üëâ the entire app would freeze.

Async JS allows long tasks to run in background without blocking the main thread.

2Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Callback
‚úÖ Definition

A callback is a function passed as an argument to another function and executed later, usually after an async task finishes.

üîπ Basic Example
function greet(name, callback) {
  console.log("Hello " + name);
  callback();
}

greet("Gaurav", () => {
  console.log("Welcome!");
});

üîπ Real Async Example (setTimeout)
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Done");
}, 1000);


‚è±Ô∏è JS says:

‚ÄúWait 1 second‚Äù

Then execute the callback

üîπ Callback Flow (Internals)

Function is registered

Browser/Node handles timer

After delay ‚Üí callback enters callback queue

Event loop pushes it to call stack

‚ùå Callback Hell (Big Problem)

Nested callbacks become unreadable.

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Step 1");

  setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Step 2");

    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log("Step 3");
    }, 1000);

  }, 1000);

}, 1000);


‚ùå Hard to read
‚ùå Hard to debug
‚ùå Hard to handle errors

‚ùå Error Handling in Callbacks
function getData(callback) {
  let error = true;

  if (error) {
    callback("Error occurred", null);
  } else {
    callback(null, "Data");
  }
}

getData((err, data) => {
  if (err) console.log(err);
  else console.log(data);
});

‚ö†Ô∏è Problems with Callbacks

Callback hell

Inversion of control

Difficult error handling

2Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Promise
‚úÖ Definition

A Promise represents a value that will be available now, later, or never.

üîπ Promise States
State	Meaning
Pending	Initial state
Fulfilled	Operation succeeded
Rejected	Operation failed
üîπ Creating a Promise
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  resolve("Success");
});

üîπ Consuming a Promise
promise
  .then(result => console.log(result))
  .catch(error => console.log(error))
  .finally(() => console.log("Done"));

üîπ Real-World Example (API Simulation)
function fetchUser() {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve({ name: "Gaurav", role: "Developer" });
    }, 1000);
  });
}

fetchUser().then(user => console.log(user));

üîπ Promise Chaining
fetchUser()
  .then(user => user.name)
  .then(name => name.toUpperCase())
  .then(console.log)
  .catch(console.error);

üîπ Promise Utility Methods ‚≠ê
Promise.all([p1, p2]);        // all succeed
Promise.race([p1, p2]);      // first settled
Promise.allSettled([p1, p2]); // success + failure
Promise.any([p1, p2]);       // first success

‚ùå Promise Problems

Still complex chaining

Nested .then() in big apps

Harder readability

2Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ Async / Await ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê
‚úÖ Definition

async/await is syntactic sugar over promises, making async code look synchronous.

üîπ Basic Example
async function fetchData() {
  return "Data loaded";
}

fetchData().then(console.log);


üëâ async function always returns a Promise

üîπ Using await
async function loadData() {
  const data = await fetchData();
  console.log(data);
}

loadData();

üîπ Real API Example
async function getUser() {
  const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/user");
  const data = await response.json();
  return data;
}

üîπ Error Handling with try / catch
async function getData() {
  try {
    const res = await fetch("invalid-url");
    const data = await res.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.log("Error:", error.message);
  }
}

üîπ Parallel vs Sequential Execution
‚ùå Slow (Sequential)
await task1();
await task2();

‚úÖ Fast (Parallel)
const [a, b] = await Promise.all([task1(), task2()]);

üß† Internals: Event Loop (Simple)
console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => console.log("Timeout"), 0);

Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log("Promise"));

console.log("End");

Output:
Start
End
Promise
Timeout


Why?

Sync first

Microtasks (Promises)

Macrotasks (setTimeout)

üìä Comparison Table
Feature	Callback	Promise	Async/Await
Readability	‚ùå Poor	‚ö†Ô∏è Medium	‚≠ê Best
Error Handling	‚ùå Hard	Better	‚≠ê Easy
Nesting	‚ùå High	Medium	‚≠ê Low
Usage Today	Legacy	Common	‚≠ê Standard

2Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Callback

Definition:
Function passed as argument.

Example:

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Done");
}, 1000);

2Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Promise

Example:

const promise = new Promise((resolve) => {
  resolve("Success");
});

promise.then(console.log);

2Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ Async / Await ‚≠ê

Example:

async function fetchData() {
  return "Data loaded";
}

console.log(await fetchData());

üü¢ PART 14: DOM
2Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ DOM Manipulation

Definition:
JavaScript can change HTML elements.

Example:

document.getElementById("title").innerText = "Hello";

üü¢ PART 15: Classes & OOP
2Ô∏è‚É£6Ô∏è‚É£ Class

Example:

class Person {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  greet() {
    console.log("Hello " + this.name);
  }
}

const p1 = new Person("Gaurav");
p1.greet();

üü¢ PART 16: Error Handling
2Ô∏è‚É£7Ô∏è‚É£ try / catch

Example:

try {
  let x = y;
} catch (error) {
  console.log("Error caught");
}

üü¢ PART 17: Modules
2Ô∏è‚É£8Ô∏è‚É£ import / export

Example:

// math.js
export const add = (a, b) => a + b;

// main.js
import { add } from "./math.js";

üü¢ PART 18: JavaScript in Backend (Node.js)
2Ô∏è‚É£9Ô∏è‚É£ Node.js

Definition:
JavaScript runtime outside browser.

Example:

const fs = require("fs");
fs.writeFileSync("test.txt", "Hello");

üü¢ PART 19: Best Practices
3Ô∏è‚É£0Ô∏è‚É£ Clean Code

Example:

// Bad
let a = 10;

// Good
let totalUsers = 10;















JavaScript Interview Questions & Answers

(Simple words ‚Ä¢ Interview-ready)

üß† CORE CONCEPTS (VERY IMPORTANT)
1Ô∏è‚É£ Why is JavaScript single-threaded?

Answer:
JavaScript runs one task at a time to avoid memory conflicts and make code predictable.
Async tasks are handled using the event loop.

2Ô∏è‚É£ What is the Event Loop?

Answer:
The event loop checks:

Call stack

Callback queue

Microtask queue
and decides what to execute next.

3Ô∏è‚É£ What is the Call Stack?

Answer:
It keeps track of function execution order.

4Ô∏è‚É£ What is the difference between microtask & macrotask?

Answer:

Microtask ‚Üí Promises (then, await)

Macrotask ‚Üí setTimeout, setInterval

üëâ Microtasks run before macrotasks.

üîÅ ASYNC / AWAIT & PROMISES
5Ô∏è‚É£ What happens if you don‚Äôt use await?

Answer:
The function continues executing without waiting for the Promise.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Can we use await without async?

Answer:
No. await works only inside async functions
(Except top-level await in modern JS).

7Ô∏è‚É£ What is Promise chaining?

Answer:
Using multiple .then() calls to handle async steps.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Difference between Promise.all and Promise.allSettled?

Answer:

Promise.all ‚Üí fails if any Promise fails

Promise.allSettled ‚Üí waits for all results

üîê SCOPE, HOISTING & MEMORY
9Ô∏è‚É£ What is hoisting?

Answer:
JavaScript moves variable and function declarations to the top before execution.

üîü Why does let not hoist like var?

Answer:
let is hoisted but stays in temporal dead zone until initialized.

1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ What is the Temporal Dead Zone?

Answer:
The time between variable creation and initialization where it cannot be accessed.

1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ What is garbage collection?

Answer:
JavaScript automatically removes unused variables from memory.

üß© CLOSURES (FAVORITE QUESTION)
1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Explain closures in simple words

Answer:
A closure is when a function remembers variables from its parent function even after execution.

1Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ Real-life use of closures?

Answer:

Counters

Authentication

Private variables

State management

üß† this KEYWORD (TRICKY)
1Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ What is this?

Answer:
this refers to the object that calls the function.

1Ô∏è‚É£6Ô∏è‚É£ Why this behaves differently in arrow functions?

Answer:
Arrow functions do not have their own this.
They use this from the parent scope.

1Ô∏è‚É£7Ô∏è‚É£ Difference between call, apply, bind?

Answer:

call ‚Üí calls function immediately

apply ‚Üí same as call but takes array

bind ‚Üí returns a new function

üßÆ ARRAY & OBJECT DEEP QUESTIONS
1Ô∏è‚É£8Ô∏è‚É£ What is shallow copy?

Answer:
Copies reference, not actual data.

1Ô∏è‚É£9Ô∏è‚É£ What is deep copy?

Answer:
Copies actual data, not reference.

2Ô∏è‚É£0Ô∏è‚É£ How to deep copy an object?

Answer:

JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))


(Works for simple objects)

‚ö° PERFORMANCE QUESTIONS
2Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ What is debouncing?

Answer:
Delays function execution until the action stops.

2Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ What is throttling?

Answer:
Limits how often a function runs.

2Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Where are debounce & throttle used?

Answer:

Search input

Scroll events

Resize events

üåê DOM & EVENTS
2Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ What is event bubbling?

Answer:
Event moves from child ‚Üí parent.

2Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ What is event capturing?

Answer:
Event moves from parent ‚Üí child.

2Ô∏è‚É£6Ô∏è‚É£ How to stop event bubbling?

Answer:

event.stopPropagation();

üì¶ MODULES & ARCHITECTURE
2Ô∏è‚É£7Ô∏è‚É£ What is modular programming?

Answer:
Splitting code into reusable files.

2Ô∏è‚É£8Ô∏è‚É£ Difference between CommonJS & ES Modules?

Answer:

CommonJS ‚Üí require

ES Modules ‚Üí import/export

üß™ OUTPUT-BASED TRICKY QUESTIONS
2Ô∏è‚É£9Ô∏è‚É£ Output?
console.log(1);
setTimeout(() => console.log(2), 0);
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log(3));
console.log(4);


‚úÖ Answer:

1
4
3
2

3Ô∏è‚É£0Ô∏è‚É£ Output?
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 1000);
}


‚úÖ Answer:

3
3
3


Reason: var has function scope.

üß† REAL INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
3Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Why choose JavaScript?

Answer:
It runs everywhere, supports async programming, and has a huge ecosystem.

3Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ What makes you a strong JavaScript developer?

Answer:
Understanding async behavior, closures, clean code, and real-world problem solving.
